oa_counting_up_down_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Counting Train Platform.

oa_counting_up_down_page0_sentence.text: I am at the counting platform. I see the number line on the wall. The numbers go from zero to twenty.

oa_counting_up_down_page0_mathtip.text: Numbers go in order. Each number is one more than the last.

oa_counting_up_down_page1_sentence.text: I start at five. I count up. Five, six, seven. I moved up by one each time.

oa_counting_up_down_page1_mathtip.text: When you count up, you add one.

oa_counting_up_down_page2_question.text: I start at 7. I count up two numbers. Where do I land?

oa_counting_up_down_page2_mathcontext.text: I am counting on the number line.

oa_counting_up_down_page2_mathhint.text: Start at seven. Count up one, then up one more.

oa_counting_up_down_page3_sentence.text: I stand at ten. I count down. Ten, nine, eight. I moved down by one each time.

oa_counting_up_down_page3_mathtip.text: When you count down, you subtract one.

oa_counting_up_down_page4_question.text: I start at 12. I count down two numbers. Where do I land?

oa_counting_up_down_page4_mathcontext.text: I am counting backward on the number line.

oa_counting_up_down_page4_mathhint.text: Start at twelve. Count down one, then down one more.

oa_counting_up_down_page5_menustory.text: The snack stand has treats. I choose one.

oa_counting_up_down_page6_sentence.text: I count the people waiting. I start at six. One more person comes. Now there are seven people.

oa_counting_up_down_page6_mathtip.text: Six plus one equals seven. That is counting up.

oa_counting_up_down_page6_mathconcept.text: Adding one is the same as counting up one

oa_counting_up_down_page7_mathcontext.text: I have eight tickets. I get one more.

oa_counting_up_down_page7_mathhint.text: Count up from eight. What number comes next?

oa_counting_up_down_page7_success.text: Yes! Eight plus one is nine. You counted up.

oa_counting_up_down_page8_sentence.text: I have nine coins. I spend one coin. Now I have eight coins left.

oa_counting_up_down_page8_mathtip.text: Nine minus one equals eight. That is counting down.

oa_counting_up_down_page8_mathconcept.text: Subtracting one is the same as counting down one

oa_counting_up_down_page9_mathcontext.text: I have eleven napkins. I use one napkin.

oa_counting_up_down_page9_mathhint.text: Count down from eleven. What number comes before?

oa_counting_up_down_page9_success.text: Nice! Eleven minus one is ten. You counted down.

oa_counting_up_down_page10_mathcontext.text: I start at five. I count up two times.

oa_counting_up_down_page10_mathhint.text: Start at five. Count up: six, seven.

oa_counting_up_down_page10_success.text: Great! You counted on from five.

oa_counting_up_down_page11_mathcontext.text: I start at nine. I count back two times.

oa_counting_up_down_page11_mathhint.text: Start at nine. Count back: eight, seven.

oa_counting_up_down_page11_success.text: Excellent! You counted back from nine.

oa_add_word_problems_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Fruit Stand Addition.

oa_add_word_problems_page0_sentence.text: I arrive at the fruit stand. I see baskets of fruit. The vendor smiles and says hello.

oa_add_word_problems_page0_mathtip.text: Word problems tell a story with numbers.

oa_add_word_problems_page0_mathconcept.text: Setting the scene for word problems

oa_add_word_problems_page1_sentence.text: I have three apples in my bag. I pick two more apples. Now I have five apples in my bag.

oa_add_word_problems_page1_mathtip.text: When you get more, you add.

oa_add_word_problems_page2_question.text: How many apples do I have now?

oa_add_word_problems_page2_mathcontext.text: I have three apples in my bag. I pick two more apples.

oa_add_word_problems_page2_mathhint.text: Count all the apples. Start with three. Add two more.

oa_add_word_problems_page2_success.text: Yes! Three plus two equals five.

oa_add_word_problems_page3_sentence.text: I see four oranges on the left shelf. I see three oranges on the right shelf. There are seven oranges in all.

oa_add_word_problems_page3_mathtip.text: Add to find how many in all.

oa_add_word_problems_page4_question.text: How many oranges are there in all?

oa_add_word_problems_page4_mathcontext.text: There are six oranges on the left. There are five oranges on the right.

oa_add_word_problems_page4_success.text: Correct! Six plus five equals eleven.

oa_add_word_problems_page5_menustory.text: The fruit looks fresh and colorful. I choose my favorite.

oa_add_word_problems_page6_question.text: How many pieces of fruit does she have now?

oa_add_word_problems_page6_mathcontext.text: My sister has seven strawberries. I give her four more strawberries.

oa_add_word_problems_page6_mathhint.text: Start with seven. Count on four more.

oa_add_word_problems_page6_success.text: Great work! Seven plus four equals eleven.

oa_add_word_problems_page7_sentence.text: The vendor puts eight pears in a basket. Then he adds five more pears to the basket. Now there are thirteen pears.

oa_add_word_problems_page7_mathtip.text: You can count on from the bigger number.

oa_add_word_problems_page8_question.text: How many fruits are in the box now?

oa_add_word_problems_page8_mathcontext.text: There are nine apples in a box. The farmer adds six more apples.

oa_add_word_problems_page8_mathhint.text: Start at nine. Count on six more: ten, eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen, fifteen.

oa_add_word_problems_page8_success.text: Excellent! Nine plus six equals fifteen.

oa_add_word_problems_page9_question.text: How many total fruits do I buy?

oa_add_word_problems_page9_mathcontext.text: I buy eight oranges and seven lemons.

oa_add_word_problems_page9_mathhint.text: Add eight and seven. You can make ten first: 8 + 2 = 10, then add 5 more.

oa_add_word_problems_page9_success.text: Perfect! Eight plus seven equals fifteen.

oa_sub_word_problems_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Noodle Shop Subtraction.

oa_sub_word_problems_page0_sentence.text: I am at the noodle shop. I see steaming bowls on the counter. The cook is busy making more noodles.

oa_sub_word_problems_page0_mathtip.text: Subtraction stories tell about things being taken away or used up.

oa_sub_word_problems_page1_sentence.text: There are seven bowls of noodles. Three customers take bowls. Now there are four bowls left.

oa_sub_word_problems_page1_mathtip.text: When you take away, you subtract.

oa_sub_word_problems_page2_mathcontext.text: There are seven bowls of noodles. Three customers take bowls.

oa_sub_word_problems_page2_mathhint.text: Start with seven. Take away three. Count what is left.

oa_sub_word_problems_page2_success.text: Yes! Seven minus three equals four.

oa_sub_word_problems_page3_sentence.text: The cook has ten eggs. She uses four eggs to make noodles. She has six eggs left.

oa_sub_word_problems_page3_mathtip.text: When you use some, subtract to find what is left.

oa_sub_word_problems_page4_mathcontext.text: There are twelve chopsticks in the jar. I take out five chopsticks.

oa_sub_word_problems_page4_mathhint.text: Start at twelve. Count back five.

oa_sub_word_problems_page4_success.text: Correct! Twelve minus five equals seven.

oa_sub_word_problems_page5_menustory.text: The menu has many choices. I pick my favorite kind of noodles.

oa_sub_word_problems_page6_question.text: How many napkins are left in the holder?

oa_sub_word_problems_page6_mathcontext.text: There are fifteen napkins in the holder. Customers use eight napkins.

oa_sub_word_problems_page6_mathhint.text: Start with fifteen. Take away eight. Count what remains.

oa_sub_word_problems_page6_success.text: Great! Fifteen minus eight equals seven.

oa_sub_word_problems_page7_sentence.text: I see fourteen dumplings on the tray. My family eats six dumplings. There are eight dumplings left on the tray.

oa_sub_word_problems_page7_mathtip.text: You can count back or think about what is left.

oa_sub_word_problems_page8_question.text: How many spring rolls are left?

oa_sub_word_problems_page8_mathcontext.text: The cook makes sixteen spring rolls. He sells nine spring rolls.

oa_sub_word_problems_page8_mathhint.text: Start at sixteen. Count back nine, or think: nine plus what equals sixteen?

oa_sub_word_problems_page8_success.text: Excellent! Sixteen minus nine equals seven.

oa_sub_word_problems_page9_question.text: How many customers are still waiting?

oa_sub_word_problems_page9_mathcontext.text: There are thirteen customers waiting. Seven customers get their food and leave.

oa_sub_word_problems_page9_mathhint.text: Start with thirteen. Take away seven. You can count back.

oa_sub_word_problems_page9_success.text: Perfect! Thirteen minus seven equals six.

oa_add_three_numbers_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Bakery Three Numbers.

oa_add_three_numbers_page0_sentence.text: I walk into the bakery. I smell fresh bread and sweet pastries. The baker shows me three trays of treats.

oa_add_three_numbers_page0_mathtip.text: When you have three numbers, you add two first, then add the third.

oa_add_three_numbers_page0_mathconcept.text: Setting up for adding three numbers

oa_add_three_numbers_page1_sentence.text: I see two croissants on the first tray. I see three croissants on the second tray. I see one croissant on the third tray. There are six croissants in all.

oa_add_three_numbers_page1_mathtip.text: Add the first two numbers. Then add the third number.

oa_add_three_numbers_page2_mathcontext.text: There are two croissants, then three croissants, then one croissant.

oa_add_three_numbers_page2_mathhint.text: Add two and three first. That makes five. Then add one more.

oa_add_three_numbers_page2_success.text: Yes! Two plus three plus one equals six.

oa_add_three_numbers_page3_sentence.text: The baker puts four cookies, two cookies, and four cookies in a bag. I can group the fours together. Four plus four equals eight. Then I add two more. The total is ten cookies.

oa_add_three_numbers_page3_mathtip.text: Look for doubles or easy pairs. Add those first.

oa_add_three_numbers_page3_mathconcept.text: Grouping numbers that are easy to add

oa_add_three_numbers_page4_mathcontext.text: I buy three muffins, five muffins, and three muffins.

oa_add_three_numbers_page4_mathhint.text: Look for the doubles. Three plus three equals six. Then add five.

oa_add_three_numbers_page4_success.text: Great! You grouped the threes first. Three plus three plus five equals eleven.

oa_add_three_numbers_page5_menustory.text: The bakery has so many delicious treats. I choose one to eat now.

oa_add_three_numbers_page6_sentence.text: I see seven rolls, three rolls, and two rolls. I notice that three and seven make ten. Then I add two more. There are twelve rolls in all.

oa_add_three_numbers_page6_mathtip.text: Look for two numbers that make ten. That makes adding easier.

oa_add_three_numbers_page6_mathconcept.text: Making ten to add three numbers

oa_add_three_numbers_page7_mathcontext.text: There are six bagels, four bagels, and three bagels.

oa_add_three_numbers_page7_mathhint.text: Six plus four makes ten. Then add three more.

oa_add_three_numbers_page7_success.text: Excellent! You made ten first. Six plus four plus three equals thirteen.

oa_add_three_numbers_page8_mathcontext.text: I count two tarts, eight tarts, and five tarts.

oa_add_three_numbers_page8_mathhint.text: Two plus eight makes ten. Then add five more.

oa_add_three_numbers_page8_success.text: Perfect! Two plus eight plus five equals fifteen.

oa_add_three_numbers_page9_mathcontext.text: The baker arranges five pies, three pies, and five pies on the shelf.

oa_add_three_numbers_page9_mathhint.text: Look for doubles. Five plus five equals ten. Then add three.

oa_add_three_numbers_page9_success.text: Wonderful! Five plus three plus five equals thirteen.

oa_fact_families_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Bubble Tea Fact Families.

oa_fact_families_page0_sentence.text: I visit the bubble tea shop. The cashier shows me three cups and four cups. She says there are seven cups in all. Then she switches them. Four cups and three cups still make seven cups.

oa_fact_families_page0_mathtip.text: You can add numbers in any order. The sum stays the same.

oa_fact_families_page1_mathhint.text: Turn-around facts have the same answer. The order does not matter.

oa_fact_families_page1_success.text: Yes! Five plus two and two plus five both equal seven.

oa_fact_families_page2_sentence.text: The worker puts six tapioca pearls in one cup and four pearls in another cup. That makes ten pearls. She tells me this is a fact family. Six plus four equals ten. Four plus six equals ten. Ten minus six equals four. Ten minus four equals six.

oa_fact_families_page2_mathtip.text: A fact family uses the same three numbers to make four facts.

oa_fact_families_page3_question.text: Which fact belongs in the same family as 3 + 5 = 8?

oa_fact_families_page3_mathcontext.text: I am learning fact families with three, five, and eight.

oa_fact_families_page3_mathhint.text: Fact families use the same three numbers. Look for three, five, and eight.

oa_fact_families_page3_success.text: Correct! Three, five, and eight make a fact family.

oa_fact_families_page4_menustory.text: The menu has many flavors. I pick my favorite bubble tea to drink.

oa_fact_families_page5_sentence.text: I use the numbers seven, two, and nine to write facts. Seven plus two equals nine. Two plus seven equals nine. Nine minus seven equals two. Nine minus two equals seven.

oa_fact_families_page5_mathtip.text: Start with addition facts. Then write subtraction facts using the same numbers.

oa_fact_families_page5_mathconcept.text: Writing all four facts in a family

oa_fact_families_page6_mathcontext.text: I use the fact family for four, five, and nine.

oa_fact_families_page6_mathhint.text: If four plus five equals nine, then nine minus four equals five.

oa_fact_families_page6_success.text: Great! You used the fact family.

oa_fact_families_page7_mathcontext.text: I use addition to help with subtraction.

oa_fact_families_page7_mathhint.text: Seven plus six equals thirteen. So thirteen minus seven equals six.

oa_fact_families_page7_success.text: Excellent! You used addition to solve subtraction.

oa_fact_families_page8_question.text: What number completes this fact family: 8 + ___ = 14, 14 - 8 = ___?

oa_fact_families_page8_mathcontext.text: I am finding the missing number in a fact family.

oa_fact_families_page8_mathhint.text: What number do you add to eight to get fourteen? That same number is the answer to fourteen minus eight.

oa_fact_families_page8_success.text: Perfect! Eight plus six equals fourteen, and fourteen minus eight equals six.

oa_fact_families_page9_mathcontext.text: I check if turn-around facts work with bigger numbers.

oa_fact_families_page9_mathhint.text: You can add in any order. The sum is the same.

oa_fact_families_page9_success.text: Yes! Nine plus five and five plus nine both equal fourteen.

oa_add_facts_20_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Dumpling Addition Facts.

oa_add_facts_20_page0_sentence.text: I arrive at the dumpling restaurant. The cook is making dumplings very fast. She knows her numbers quickly. I will practice my addition facts to get fast too.

oa_add_facts_20_page0_mathtip.text: Practice helps you get faster and more accurate.

oa_add_facts_20_page1_mathcontext.text: I count dumplings. Six plus six is a double.

oa_add_facts_20_page1_mathhint.text: Six plus six is a double. What is double six?

oa_add_facts_20_page1_success.text: Yes! Six plus six equals twelve.

oa_add_facts_20_page2_mathcontext.text: There are nine dumplings. I add one more.

oa_add_facts_20_page2_mathhint.text: Nine plus one is just counting up one from nine.

oa_add_facts_20_page2_success.text: Correct! Nine plus one equals ten.

oa_add_facts_20_page3_mathcontext.text: I group seven dumplings and three dumplings.

oa_add_facts_20_page3_success.text: Great! Seven plus three equals ten.

oa_add_facts_20_page4_menustory.text: The restaurant has different kinds of dumplings. I choose my favorite.

oa_add_facts_20_page5_mathcontext.text: I add seven dumplings and eight dumplings.

oa_add_facts_20_page5_mathhint.text: Think of the double seven plus seven equals fourteen. Then add one more.

oa_add_facts_20_page5_success.text: Excellent! Seven plus eight equals fifteen.

oa_add_facts_20_page6_mathcontext.text: The cook puts five dumplings and seven dumplings on the tray.

oa_add_facts_20_page6_mathhint.text: You can make ten first. Five plus five equals ten. Then add two more.

oa_add_facts_20_page6_success.text: Nice work! Five plus seven equals twelve.

oa_add_facts_20_page7_mathcontext.text: I count nine dumplings and seven dumplings.

oa_add_facts_20_page7_mathhint.text: Nine plus one equals ten. Then add six more. Ten plus six equals sixteen.

oa_add_facts_20_page7_success.text: Perfect! Nine plus seven equals sixteen.

oa_add_facts_20_page8_mathcontext.text: There are eight steamed dumplings and six fried dumplings.

oa_add_facts_20_page8_mathhint.text: Eight plus two makes ten. Then add four more.

oa_add_facts_20_page8_success.text: Wonderful! Eight plus six equals fourteen.

oa_sub_facts_20_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Rice Bowl Subtraction Facts.

oa_sub_facts_20_page0_sentence.text: I am at the rice bowl shop. The server is very quick with numbers. She can subtract fast. I will practice my subtraction facts.

oa_sub_facts_20_page0_mathtip.text: Knowing your subtraction facts helps you solve problems quickly.

oa_sub_facts_20_page1_mathcontext.text: There are ten bowls. One customer takes a bowl.

oa_sub_facts_20_page1_mathhint.text: Ten minus one is just counting back one from ten.

oa_sub_facts_20_page1_success.text: Yes! Ten minus one equals nine.

oa_sub_facts_20_page2_mathcontext.text: I have ten grains of rice. I eat four grains.

oa_sub_facts_20_page2_mathhint.text: Think: four plus what equals ten? Four plus six equals ten.

oa_sub_facts_20_page2_success.text: Correct! Ten minus four equals six.

oa_sub_facts_20_page3_mathcontext.text: There are eight spoons. Three spoons are used.

oa_sub_facts_20_page3_mathhint.text: Count back three from eight: seven, six, five.

oa_sub_facts_20_page3_success.text: Great! Eight minus three equals five.

oa_sub_facts_20_page4_menustory.text: The menu has rice bowls with different toppings. I pick one.

oa_sub_facts_20_page5_mathcontext.text: The cook makes twelve bowls. Five bowls are sold.

oa_sub_facts_20_page5_mathhint.text: Think: five plus what equals twelve? Five plus seven equals twelve.

oa_sub_facts_20_page5_success.text: Excellent! Twelve minus five equals seven.

oa_sub_facts_20_page6_mathcontext.text: I see fifteen chopsticks. Seven are taken away.

oa_sub_facts_20_page6_mathhint.text: Think: seven plus what equals fifteen? Seven plus eight equals fifteen.

oa_sub_facts_20_page6_success.text: Perfect! Fifteen minus seven equals eight.

oa_sub_facts_20_page7_mathcontext.text: There are thirteen napkins. Eight napkins are used.

oa_sub_facts_20_page7_mathhint.text: Think: eight plus what equals thirteen? Eight plus five equals thirteen.

oa_sub_facts_20_page7_success.text: Wonderful! Thirteen minus eight equals five.

oa_sub_facts_20_page8_mathcontext.text: The restaurant has seventeen tables. Nine tables are full.

oa_sub_facts_20_page8_mathhint.text: Think: nine plus what equals seventeen? Nine plus eight equals seventeen.

oa_sub_facts_20_page8_success.text: Amazing! Seventeen minus nine equals eight.

oa_equal_sign_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Balance Scale Station.

oa_equal_sign_page0_sentence.text: I walk into the balance scale station. The worker shows me a scale. She says the equal sign is like a balance. Both sides must be the same.

oa_equal_sign_page0_mathtip.text: Equal means the left side and right side have the same value.

oa_equal_sign_page0_mathconcept.text: The equal sign means both sides are the same

oa_equal_sign_page1_sentence.text: I see the equation three equals three. The worker says this is true. Three on the left and three on the right are the same.

oa_equal_sign_page1_mathtip.text: If both sides are equal, the equation is true.

oa_equal_sign_page2_mathcontext.text: I check if both sides are equal.

oa_equal_sign_page2_mathhint.text: Is five the same as five? Yes, so it is true.

oa_equal_sign_page2_success.text: Yes! Five equals five is true.

oa_equal_sign_page3_sentence.text: I see another equation. Four plus one equals five. The worker puts four blocks and one block on the left. She puts five blocks on the right. The scale balances. It is true.

oa_equal_sign_page3_mathtip.text: Check both sides. If they are the same, it is true.

oa_equal_sign_page3_mathconcept.text: Equations with operations can be true

oa_equal_sign_page4_mathcontext.text: I check if three plus two equals five.

oa_equal_sign_page4_mathhint.text: Add three and two. Does it equal five? Yes, so it is true.

oa_equal_sign_page4_success.text: Correct! Three plus two equals five, so it is true.

oa_equal_sign_page5_menustory.text: The station has different balance activities. I choose one to try.

oa_equal_sign_page6_sentence.text: I try an equation that is false. The worker shows me six equals seven. She says this is false. Six and seven are not the same. The scale does not balance.

oa_equal_sign_page6_mathtip.text: If both sides are different, the equation is false.

oa_equal_sign_page7_mathcontext.text: I check if eight equals nine.

oa_equal_sign_page7_mathhint.text: Are eight and nine the same? No, so it is false.

oa_equal_sign_page7_success.text: Yes! Eight does not equal nine, so it is false.

oa_equal_sign_page8_mathcontext.text: I check if five plus three equals nine.

oa_equal_sign_page8_mathhint.text: Add five and three. Does it equal nine? No, five plus three equals eight.

oa_equal_sign_page8_success.text: Correct! Five plus three equals eight, not nine. It is false.

oa_equal_sign_page9_mathcontext.text: I check if both sides are equal. The left side is four plus three. The right side is two plus five.

oa_equal_sign_page9_mathhint.text: Add both sides. Four plus three equals seven. Two plus five equals seven. Both sides are seven.

oa_equal_sign_page9_success.text: Excellent! Both sides equal seven, so it is true.

oa_equal_sign_page10_mathcontext.text: I check if ten minus four equals six.

oa_equal_sign_page10_mathhint.text: Subtract four from ten. Does it equal six? Yes.

oa_equal_sign_page10_success.text: Perfect! Ten minus four equals six, so it is true.

oa_missing_number_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Mystery Number Station.

oa_missing_number_page0_sentence.text: I enter the mystery number station. The detective shows me equations with missing numbers. She says I need to find what number goes in the blank to make it true.

oa_missing_number_page0_mathtip.text: The missing number makes the equation true.

oa_missing_number_page1_sentence.text: I see my first mystery. Three plus blank equals seven. I think: three plus what makes seven? Three plus four makes seven. The missing number is four.

oa_missing_number_page1_mathtip.text: Ask yourself: what do I add to get the answer?

oa_missing_number_page2_question.text: What number goes in the blank? 5 + ___ = 8

oa_missing_number_page2_mathcontext.text: I need to find the missing number.

oa_missing_number_page2_mathhint.text: Five plus what equals eight? Think: five plus three equals eight.

oa_missing_number_page2_success.text: Yes! Five plus three equals eight.

oa_missing_number_page3_sentence.text: The detective shows me a new mystery. Blank plus six equals ten. I think: what plus six makes ten? Four plus six makes ten. The missing number is four.

oa_missing_number_page3_mathtip.text: It does not matter where the blank is. Think about what makes it true.

oa_missing_number_page4_question.text: What number goes in the blank? ___ + 4 = 9

oa_missing_number_page4_mathcontext.text: The missing number is at the beginning.

oa_missing_number_page4_mathhint.text: What plus four equals nine? Think: five plus four equals nine.

oa_missing_number_page4_success.text: Correct! Five plus four equals nine.

oa_missing_number_page5_menustory.text: The detective has different mystery cases. I choose one to solve.

oa_missing_number_page6_sentence.text: Now I see a subtraction mystery. Twelve minus blank equals five. I think: twelve minus what makes five? Twelve minus seven makes five. The missing number is seven.

oa_missing_number_page6_mathtip.text: For subtraction, think: what do I take away to get the answer?

oa_missing_number_page7_question.text: What number goes in the blank? 10 - ___ = 6

oa_missing_number_page7_mathcontext.text: I need to find what number to subtract.

oa_missing_number_page7_mathhint.text: Ten minus what equals six? Think: ten minus four equals six.

oa_missing_number_page7_success.text: Great! Ten minus four equals six.

oa_missing_number_page8_question.text: What number goes in the blank? 8 + ___ = 15

oa_missing_number_page8_mathcontext.text: I find the missing addend with larger numbers.

oa_missing_number_page8_mathhint.text: Eight plus what equals fifteen? Count on from eight or think: eight plus seven equals fifteen.

oa_missing_number_page8_success.text: Excellent! Eight plus seven equals fifteen.

oa_missing_number_page9_question.text: What number goes in the blank? ___ - 5 = 9

oa_missing_number_page9_mathcontext.text: The missing number is the starting number.

oa_missing_number_page9_mathhint.text: What number minus five equals nine? Think: nine plus five equals fourteen. So fourteen minus five equals nine.

oa_missing_number_page9_success.text: Perfect! Fourteen minus five equals nine.

oa_missing_number_page10_question.text: What number goes in the blank? 13 - ___ = 6

oa_missing_number_page10_mathcontext.text: I solve a harder subtraction mystery.

oa_missing_number_page10_mathhint.text: Thirteen minus what equals six? Think: six plus seven equals thirteen. So thirteen minus seven equals six.

oa_missing_number_page10_success.text: Amazing! Thirteen minus seven equals six.

nbt_count_to_120_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Train Number Station.

nbt_count_to_120_page0_sentence.text: I am at the train number station. I see train numbers on the platform. The trains have big numbers from 1 to 120.

nbt_count_to_120_page0_mathtip.text: Numbers go in order. Each number is one more than the last.

nbt_count_to_120_page0_mathconcept.text: We can count all the way to 120.

nbt_count_to_120_page1_mathcontext.text: I count the trains. I see train 19. What is the next train number?

nbt_count_to_120_page1_mathhint.text: Count up. After 19 comes the next number.

nbt_count_to_120_page1_success.text: Yes! After 19 comes 20. You counted up!

nbt_count_to_120_page2_sentence.text: I count past 99. After 99 comes 100. One hundred! Then 101, 102, 103. The numbers keep going.

nbt_count_to_120_page2_mathtip.text: 100 is a big number. It is 10 tens. After 100, we keep counting.

nbt_count_to_120_page3_mathcontext.text: I see train 99 pull into the station. The next train arrives. What number is it?

nbt_count_to_120_page3_mathhint.text: After 99, we reach one hundred. That is 100.

nbt_count_to_120_page3_success.text: Great! After 99 comes 100. That is one hundred!

nbt_count_to_120_page4_sentence.text: I practice counting. 108, 109, 110. I read each number out loud. One hundred eight. One hundred nine. One hundred ten.

nbt_count_to_120_page4_mathtip.text: Say the hundreds part first. Then the tens and ones.

nbt_count_to_120_page5_menustory.text: The snack cart comes by. I am hungry. I pick a snack to eat on my train ride.

nbt_count_to_120_page6_mathcontext.text: I count the train cars. I count 110 cars. Then I count one more. What number?

nbt_count_to_120_page6_mathhint.text: Count up from 110. The next number is 111.

nbt_count_to_120_page6_success.text: Perfect! After 110 comes 111. You are counting past 100!

nbt_count_to_120_page7_sentence.text: I count train 115, train 116, train 117. I am getting close to 120! The last train is train 120.

nbt_count_to_120_page7_mathtip.text: Practice counting. Say the numbers in order.

nbt_count_to_120_page7_mathconcept.text: 120 is a big number. We can count all the way there.

nbt_count_to_120_page8_mathcontext.text: One train number is covered with steam. I see 117 and 119. What number is in the middle?

nbt_count_to_120_page9_mathcontext.text: Train 120 is the last train. What train comes right before it?

nbt_count_to_120_page9_mathhint.text: Count back one from 120. What is one less than 120?

nbt_tens_and_ones_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Dumpling Counting Shop.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page0_sentence.text: I am at the dumpling shop. Dumplings come in boxes of 10. I can count the boxes and the extra dumplings.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page0_mathtip.text: A ten is a group of 10 ones.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page1_sentence.text: I have 10 dumplings. I put them in one box. 10 ones equal 1 ten! The box has 10 dumplings inside.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page1_mathtip.text: When you have 10 ones, you can trade them for 1 ten.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page2_mathcontext.text: The shop worker fills a box. How many dumplings go in the box to make 1 ten?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page3_sentence.text: I count my dumplings. I have 2 boxes and 3 extra dumplings. That is 2 tens and 3 ones. The number is 23.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page3_mathtip.text: The tens digit shows how many tens. The ones digit shows how many ones.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page3_mathconcept.text: We write numbers using tens and ones.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page4_question.text: I have 2 tens and 3 ones. What number is that?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page4_mathcontext.text: I count 2 boxes of dumplings and 3 extra dumplings. What number do I have?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page5_menustory.text: The shop has many flavors. I choose my favorite kind of dumplings.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page6_sentence.text: I see 35 dumplings. How many tens? How many ones? I count 3 tens and 5 ones. 35 has 3 tens and 5 ones.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page6_mathtip.text: The first digit shows tens. The second digit shows ones.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page6_mathconcept.text: Every two-digit number has a tens digit and a ones digit.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page7_mathcontext.text: I have 35 dumplings. I count the boxes of 10. How many tens?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page7_mathhint.text: Look at the tens digit. 35 has 3 tens.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page8_mathcontext.text: I have 35 dumplings. I count the extra dumplings not in a box. How many ones?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page8_mathhint.text: Look at the ones digit. 35 has 5 ones.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page9_sentence.text: The worker bundles 10 dumplings into a new box. I watch the trade. 10 ones become 1 ten. That is how we make tens!

nbt_tens_and_ones_page9_mathtip.text: When you have 10 or more ones, make a new ten.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page9_mathconcept.text: We can trade 10 ones for 1 ten.

nbt_tens_and_ones_page10_question.text: I have 4 tens and 6 ones. What number?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page10_mathcontext.text: I build a number with base-ten blocks. I use 4 tens rods and 6 ones cubes. What number did I make?

nbt_tens_and_ones_page10_mathhint.text: Put the tens digit first, then the ones digit. 4 tens and 6 ones is 46.

nbt_teen_numbers_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Boba Tea Counter.

nbt_teen_numbers_page0_sentence.text: I am at the boba tea shop. I count the boba pearls. Teen numbers are special. They all have 1 ten and some ones.

nbt_teen_numbers_page0_mathtip.text: Every teen number has 1 ten. Then we add the extra ones.

nbt_teen_numbers_page1_sentence.text: I count 13 boba pearls. 13 is 1 ten and 3 ones. I fill one ten frame. Then I have 3 more pearls.

nbt_teen_numbers_page1_mathtip.text: Teen numbers are 10 and some more ones.

nbt_teen_numbers_page2_question.text: 13 is the same as 10 plus what?

nbt_teen_numbers_page2_mathcontext.text: I have 13 boba pearls. I know 10 fill one cup. How many extra pearls do I have?

nbt_teen_numbers_page2_mathhint.text: 13 is 10 plus 3. Think: 1 ten and 3 ones.

nbt_teen_numbers_page3_sentence.text: I make 15. I put 10 pearls in a cup. Then I add 5 more pearls. 15 is 1 ten and 5 ones. All teen numbers work this way!

nbt_teen_numbers_page3_mathtip.text: Find the ten first. Then add the extra ones.

nbt_teen_numbers_page4_mathcontext.text: I count 15 boba pearls. How many groups of 10 do I have?

nbt_teen_numbers_page5_menustory.text: The boba shop has yummy drinks. I pick my favorite flavor to drink.

nbt_teen_numbers_page6_sentence.text: I practice teen numbers. 11 is 10 and 1. 12 is 10 and 2. 17 is 10 and 7. 19 is 10 and 9. They all have 1 ten!

nbt_teen_numbers_page6_mathtip.text: Teen numbers always start with 1 ten.

nbt_teen_numbers_page6_mathconcept.text: All numbers from 11 to 19 have 1 ten and some ones.

nbt_teen_numbers_page7_mathcontext.text: I have 17 pearls. I fill one cup with 10. How many pearls are left?

nbt_teen_numbers_page8_question.text: What number is 1 ten and 4 ones?

nbt_teen_numbers_page8_mathcontext.text: I build a number. I use 1 ten rod and 4 ones cubes. What number is it?

nbt_teen_numbers_page9_sentence.text: The biggest teen number is 19. 19 is 1 ten and 9 ones. After 19 comes 20. 20 has 2 tens and 0 ones!

nbt_teen_numbers_page9_mathtip.text: After the teens, we get numbers with 2 tens, 3 tens, and more.

nbt_teen_numbers_page9_mathconcept.text: 19 is the last teen number. Then comes 20.

nbt_teen_numbers_page10_question.text: I have 1 ten and 9 ones. What number?

nbt_teen_numbers_page10_mathcontext.text: I count my boba pearls. I have 1 full cup of 10 and 9 extra pearls. What number is that?

nbt_count_by_tens_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Egg Tart Tower.

nbt_count_by_tens_page0_sentence.text: I am at the egg tart tower. The tarts come in trays of 10. I can count by tens. 10, 20, 30!

nbt_count_by_tens_page0_mathtip.text: Count by tens: 10, 20, 30, 40. Each time we add 10 more.

nbt_count_by_tens_page0_mathconcept.text: We can skip count by tens.

nbt_count_by_tens_page1_sentence.text: I count the trays. 10, 20, 30, 40, 50. Five trays is 50 tarts! When I count by tens, I add 10 each time.

nbt_count_by_tens_page1_mathtip.text: 10, 20, 30, 40, 50. Notice: they all end in zero!

nbt_count_by_tens_page1_mathconcept.text: Counting by tens means adding 10 each time.

nbt_count_by_tens_page2_question.text: Count by tens. What comes after 30?

nbt_count_by_tens_page2_mathcontext.text: I count the trays. 10, 20, 30, and then what?

nbt_count_by_tens_page2_success.text: Yes! When counting by tens, after 30 comes 40!

nbt_count_by_tens_page3_sentence.text: All tens end in zero. 10 has a 0. 20 has a 0. 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90. They all end in 0! That is how we know they are tens.

nbt_count_by_tens_page3_mathtip.text: When a number ends in 0, it has 0 ones. Only tens!

nbt_count_by_tens_page3_mathconcept.text: Numbers that are only tens end in 0.

nbt_count_by_tens_page4_mathcontext.text: I have 50 egg tarts in trays. All trays are full. How many extra tarts not in a tray?

nbt_count_by_tens_page4_mathhint.text: 50 is 5 tens and 0 ones. So there are 0 ones.

nbt_count_by_tens_page4_success.text: Perfect! 50 has 0 ones. It is all tens!

nbt_count_by_tens_page5_menustory.text: The bakery has fresh treats. I choose a yummy pastry to eat.

nbt_count_by_tens_page6_sentence.text: I keep counting by tens. 60, 70, 80, 90, 100! I can count all the way to 100 by tens. That is 10 tens!

nbt_count_by_tens_page6_mathtip.text: Count by tens to reach 100 quickly.

nbt_count_by_tens_page7_question.text: Count by tens. What comes after 70?

nbt_count_by_tens_page7_mathcontext.text: I count the trays. 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, and then?

nbt_count_by_tens_page7_mathhint.text: Keep counting by tens. After 70 comes 80.

nbt_count_by_tens_page7_success.text: Great! After 70 comes 80 when counting by tens!

nbt_count_by_tens_page8_mathcontext.text: I have 70 egg tarts. They are all in trays of 10. How many trays?

nbt_count_by_tens_page8_mathhint.text: 70 is 7 tens and 0 ones. Count the tens: 7.

nbt_count_by_tens_page9_sentence.text: Counting by tens is fast! I do not count one by one. I jump by tens. 10, 20, 30, 40. I can count many things quickly!

nbt_count_by_tens_page9_mathtip.text: Use tens to count large groups quickly.

nbt_count_by_tens_page9_mathconcept.text: Skip counting by tens is faster than counting by ones.

nbt_count_by_tens_page10_mathcontext.text: One tray number is hidden. I see 40, 50, blank, 70. What is the missing number?

nbt_compare_numbers_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Noodle Length Shop.

nbt_compare_numbers_page0_sentence.text: I am at the noodle shop. Noodles come in different bowl sizes. I can compare the numbers to see which is greater.

nbt_compare_numbers_page0_mathtip.text: Greater means bigger. Less means smaller.

nbt_compare_numbers_page0_mathconcept.text: We can compare two numbers to see which is greater or less.

nbt_compare_numbers_page1_sentence.text: I compare 35 and 42. I check the tens first. 35 has 3 tens. 42 has 4 tens. 4 tens is more than 3 tens. So 42 is greater than 35.

nbt_compare_numbers_page1_mathtip.text: The number with more tens is greater.

nbt_compare_numbers_page1_mathconcept.text: To compare numbers, check the tens digit first.

nbt_compare_numbers_page2_mathcontext.text: I see two noodle bowls. One has 27 noodles. One has 54 noodles. Which bowl has more?

nbt_compare_numbers_page2_mathhint.text: Compare tens first. 27 has 2 tens. 54 has 5 tens. 5 tens is more.

nbt_compare_numbers_page2_success.text: Yes! 54 is greater than 27 because 5 tens is more than 2 tens!

nbt_compare_numbers_page3_sentence.text: Sometimes the tens are the same. Then I check the ones. 43 and 47 both have 4 tens. But 47 has 7 ones and 43 has 3 ones. 7 ones is more than 3 ones. So 47 is greater.

nbt_compare_numbers_page3_mathtip.text: Same tens? Check which has more ones.

nbt_compare_numbers_page3_mathconcept.text: When tens are equal, compare the ones.

nbt_compare_numbers_page4_mathcontext.text: Two bowls both have 6 tens. One has 2 ones, one has 8 ones. Which is greater?

nbt_compare_numbers_page4_mathhint.text: The tens are the same. Check the ones. 8 ones is more than 2 ones.

nbt_compare_numbers_page4_success.text: Perfect! 68 is greater than 62 because 8 ones is more than 2 ones!

nbt_compare_numbers_page5_menustory.text: The noodle shop has many kinds. I choose my favorite noodles to eat.

nbt_compare_numbers_page6_sentence.text: I use the symbols to compare. The symbol for greater than is the greater than sign. The symbol for less than is the less than sign. 56 is greater than 34. 34 is less than 56.

nbt_compare_numbers_page6_mathtip.text: The greater than sign points to the smaller number. The less than sign points to the bigger number.

nbt_compare_numbers_page6_mathconcept.text: We use symbols to show comparisons: greater than, less than, equal to.

nbt_compare_numbers_page7_mathcontext.text: I compare two numbers. Which one is smaller?

nbt_compare_numbers_page7_mathhint.text: Less means smaller. 71 has 7 tens, 89 has 8 tens. 71 is less.

nbt_compare_numbers_page8_sentence.text: Sometimes two numbers are equal. 45 equals 45. They are the same! When numbers are equal, we use the equal sign.

nbt_compare_numbers_page8_mathtip.text: Equal means exactly the same amount.

nbt_compare_numbers_page8_mathconcept.text: When two numbers are the same, they are equal.

nbt_compare_numbers_page9_question.text: Is 52 greater than, less than, or equal to 52?

nbt_compare_numbers_page9_mathcontext.text: I have two bowls. Each has 52 noodles. How do the numbers compare?

nbt_compare_numbers_page9_mathhint.text: 52 and 52 are the same number. They are equal.

nbt_compare_numbers_page9_success.text: Yes! 52 equals 52. They are the same!

nbt_compare_numbers_page10_mathcontext.text: I compare 38 and 41. Which number is bigger?

nbt_compare_numbers_page10_mathhint.text: Check tens first. 38 has 3 tens, 41 has 4 tens. 41 is greater.

nbt_add_no_regroup_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Fruit Stand Addition.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page0_sentence.text: I am at the fruit stand. I buy apples and oranges. I can add the numbers together. I add ones first, then tens.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page0_mathtip.text: Line up the tens and ones. Add each place separately.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page0_mathconcept.text: To add two-digit numbers, add the ones first, then add the tens.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page1_sentence.text: I have 23 apples. I buy 5 more apples. How many apples do I have now? I add the ones. 3 plus 5 equals 8 ones. The tens stay 2 tens. 23 plus 5 equals 28.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page1_mathtip.text: 23 + 5: Add ones 3 + 5 = 8. Keep the tens. Answer: 28.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page1_mathconcept.text: When adding, start with the ones place.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page2_mathcontext.text: I have 23 apples. I add 5 more apples. How many apples in all?

nbt_add_no_regroup_page2_mathhint.text: Add the ones. 3 + 5 = 8. The tens stay 2. So 23 + 5 = 28.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page3_sentence.text: Now I try adding tens and ones together. I have 34 fruits. I buy 21 more fruits. I add ones first. 4 plus 1 equals 5 ones. Then I add tens. 3 tens plus 2 tens equals 5 tens. 34 plus 21 equals 55.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page4_mathcontext.text: I count 34 apples and 21 oranges. How many fruits in total?

nbt_add_no_regroup_page4_success.text: Excellent! 34 + 21 = 55. You added ones then tens!

nbt_add_no_regroup_page5_menustory.text: The fruit stand has fresh fruit. I choose my favorite kind to buy.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page6_sentence.text: I practice more addition. 52 plus 33. Ones: 2 plus 3 equals 5. Tens: 5 tens plus 3 tens equals 8 tens. 52 plus 33 equals 85!

nbt_add_no_regroup_page6_mathtip.text: Use base-ten blocks to see the tens and ones clearly.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page6_mathconcept.text: Always add ones first, then tens.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page7_mathcontext.text: I have 52 fruits in one basket and 33 fruits in another. How many fruits in all?

nbt_add_no_regroup_page7_success.text: Great! 52 + 33 = 85. You used the add ones then tens strategy!

nbt_add_no_regroup_page8_mathcontext.text: I buy 40 apples and 26 oranges. How many fruits do I have?

nbt_add_no_regroup_page9_sentence.text: Adding is easy when I follow the steps. Add ones. Add tens. Check my answer. I can add any two numbers this way!

nbt_add_no_regroup_page9_mathtip.text: Practice makes addition faster and easier!

nbt_add_no_regroup_page9_mathconcept.text: Use a strategy: add ones, then add tens.

nbt_add_no_regroup_page10_mathcontext.text: I count 14 red apples and 32 green apples. How many apples in total?

nbt_add_with_regroup_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Steamed Bun Kitchen.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page0_sentence.text: I am at the steamed bun kitchen. Sometimes when I add, I get 10 or more ones. Then I need to make a new ten! This is called regrouping.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page0_mathtip.text: Watch for when ones reach 10. Trade 10 ones for 1 ten.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page0_mathconcept.text: When ones add up to 10 or more, we regroup and make a new ten.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page1_sentence.text: I have 27 buns. I add 8 more buns. First I add the ones. 7 plus 8 equals 15. That is 1 ten and 5 ones! I trade 10 ones for 1 new ten. Now I have 3 tens and 5 ones. 27 plus 8 equals 35.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page1_mathtip.text: 7 + 8 = 15. That is 1 ten and 5 ones. Regroup!

nbt_add_with_regroup_page1_mathconcept.text: When ones equal 10 or more, regroup to make a new ten.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page2_mathcontext.text: I have 27 buns in baskets. I add 8 more buns. How many buns now?

nbt_add_with_regroup_page2_mathhint.text: Add ones: 7 + 8 = 15. That is 1 ten and 5 ones. Regroup! 2 tens + 1 ten = 3 tens. Answer: 35.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page2_success.text: Excellent! 27 + 8 = 35. You regrouped 15 ones into 1 ten and 5 ones!

nbt_add_with_regroup_page3_sentence.text: I try another one. 36 plus 17. Ones: 6 plus 7 equals 13. That is 1 ten and 3 ones. I regroup! Tens: 3 tens plus 1 ten plus the new ten equals 5 tens. 36 plus 17 equals 53.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page3_mathtip.text: 6 + 7 = 13. Regroup to 1 ten and 3 ones. Then add tens: 3 + 1 + 1 = 5 tens.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page3_mathconcept.text: Add ones, regroup if needed, then add all the tens.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page4_mathcontext.text: I make 36 buns in the morning and 17 buns in the afternoon. How many buns in total?

nbt_add_with_regroup_page4_mathhint.text: Ones: 6 + 7 = 13. Regroup to 1 ten and 3 ones. Tens: 3 + 1 + 1 = 5. Answer: 53.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page5_menustory.text: The kitchen makes different buns. I choose my favorite filling.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page6_sentence.text: Regrouping happens when the ones add up to 10 or more. I always check. Do I have 10 or more ones? If yes, I make a new ten!

nbt_add_with_regroup_page6_mathtip.text: When ones reach 10, trade for 1 ten. Then add the tens.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page6_mathconcept.text: Check if ones equal 10 or more. If yes, regroup.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page7_mathcontext.text: I have 48 buns on one tray and 26 buns on another. How many buns in all?

nbt_add_with_regroup_page7_mathhint.text: Ones: 8 + 6 = 14. Regroup to 1 ten and 4 ones. Tens: 4 + 2 + 1 = 7. Answer: 74.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page8_sentence.text: I practice more. 29 plus 15. Ones: 9 plus 5 equals 14. Regroup to 1 ten and 4 ones. Tens: 2 plus 1 plus 1 equals 4 tens. 29 plus 15 equals 44.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page8_mathtip.text: Follow the steps: add ones, regroup if needed, add tens.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page9_mathcontext.text: The baker makes 29 buns in the first batch and 15 in the second. How many total?

nbt_add_with_regroup_page10_mathcontext.text: I count 57 pork buns and 38 veggie buns. How many buns in total?

nbt_add_with_regroup_page10_mathhint.text: Ones: 7 + 8 = 15. Regroup to 1 ten and 5 ones. Tens: 5 + 3 + 1 = 9. Answer: 95.

nbt_add_with_regroup_page10_success.text: Excellent! 57 + 38 = 95. You are a regrouping expert!

nbt_ten_more_less_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Elevator Number Buttons.

nbt_ten_more_less_page0_sentence.text: I am at the elevator. The buttons go up and down. I can go 10 floors up or 10 floors down. This helps me practice 10 more and 10 less.

nbt_ten_more_less_page0_mathtip.text: When you add or subtract 10, only the tens digit changes.

nbt_ten_more_less_page0_mathconcept.text: Adding 10 means going up 10. Subtracting 10 means going down 10.

nbt_ten_more_less_page1_sentence.text: I am on floor 34. I press the up button. The elevator goes up 10 floors. 34 plus 10 equals 44. I am now on floor 44. The tens changed from 3 to 4. The ones stayed 4.

nbt_ten_more_less_page1_mathtip.text: To find 10 more, add 1 ten. The ones stay the same.

nbt_ten_more_less_page1_mathconcept.text: 10 more than a number means add 1 to the tens digit.

nbt_ten_more_less_page2_mathcontext.text: I am on floor 34. I go up 10 floors. What floor am I on now?

nbt_ten_more_less_page2_mathhint.text: Add 1 to the tens digit. 34 becomes 44.

nbt_ten_more_less_page3_sentence.text: Now I press the down button. I am on floor 56. I go down 10 floors. 56 minus 10 equals 46. The tens changed from 5 to 4. The ones stayed 6.

nbt_ten_more_less_page3_mathtip.text: To find 10 less, subtract 1 ten. The ones stay the same.

nbt_ten_more_less_page3_mathconcept.text: 10 less than a number means subtract 1 from the tens digit.

nbt_ten_more_less_page4_mathcontext.text: I am on floor 56. I go down 10 floors. What floor am I on?

nbt_ten_more_less_page4_mathhint.text: Subtract 1 from the tens digit. 56 becomes 46.

nbt_ten_more_less_page5_menustory.text: The elevator plays music. I choose which song I want to hear.

nbt_ten_more_less_page6_sentence.text: I can do this in my head! I do not need to write it down. I just think about the tens digit. 10 more than 72? The tens goes from 7 to 8. That is 82!

nbt_ten_more_less_page6_mathtip.text: Mental math means doing math in your head. It is fast!

nbt_ten_more_less_page6_mathconcept.text: We can find 10 more or 10 less mentally.

nbt_ten_more_less_page7_mathcontext.text: I am on floor 72. The elevator goes up 10 floors. What floor now?

nbt_ten_more_less_page8_mathcontext.text: I start on floor 83. I go down 10 floors. Where am I?

nbt_ten_more_less_page9_sentence.text: I ride the elevator all day. Up 10, down 10. The pattern is easy. Only the tens digit changes. The ones stay exactly the same every time!

nbt_ten_more_less_page9_mathtip.text: Look for the pattern. This makes mental math easier!

nbt_ten_more_less_page9_mathconcept.text: The ones digit never changes when adding or subtracting 10.

nbt_ten_more_less_page10_mathcontext.text: I am on floor 91. I press the up button to go up 10 floors. What floor?

nbt_ten_more_less_page10_mathhint.text: 9 tens plus 1 ten equals 10 tens. That is 100! 91 + 10 = 101.

nbt_ten_more_less_page10_success.text: Excellent! 10 more than 91 is 101. You went past 100!

nbt_subtract_tens_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Rice Ball Subtraction.

nbt_subtract_tens_page0_sentence.text: I am at the rice ball shop. Rice balls come in packs of 10. I can subtract tens to find how many are left.

nbt_subtract_tens_page0_mathtip.text: Subtract tens just like subtracting ones, but in the tens place.

nbt_subtract_tens_page0_mathconcept.text: We can subtract multiples of 10 from two-digit numbers.

nbt_subtract_tens_page1_sentence.text: I have 60 rice balls. That is 6 packs of 10. I give away 20 rice balls. That is 2 packs. I take away 2 tens. 6 tens minus 2 tens equals 4 tens. 60 minus 20 equals 40.

nbt_subtract_tens_page1_mathconcept.text: To subtract multiples of 10, subtract the tens.

nbt_subtract_tens_page2_mathcontext.text: I have 60 rice balls. I sell 20 rice balls. How many do I have left?

nbt_subtract_tens_page2_mathhint.text: Think tens. 6 tens - 2 tens = 4 tens. So 60 - 20 = 40.

g_2d_shapes_page12_success.text: Nice! A circle has no corners.

g_3d_shapes_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Drink Station.

g_3d_shapes_page0_sentence.text: I arrive at the Drink Station. I see many drinks. The drinks come in 3D shapes. 3D shapes are solid. They are not flat.

g_3d_shapes_page0_mathtip.text: 3D means solid. You can hold 3D shapes in your hand.

g_3d_shapes_page0_mathconcept.text: 3D shapes are solid shapes that are not flat

g_3d_shapes_page1_mathcontext.text: The drinks come in 3D shapes. 3D shapes are solid. They are not flat.

g_3d_shapes_page1_mathhint.text: Read the sentence. What word describes 3D shapes?

g_3d_shapes_page2_sentence.text: I see a juice box. The juice box is a rectangular prism. It has 6 flat faces. It has 12 edges. It looks like a box.

g_3d_shapes_page2_mathtip.text: A rectangular prism is like a box. Count the flat sides.

g_3d_shapes_page2_mathconcept.text: A rectangular prism has 6 faces and 12 edges

g_3d_shapes_page3_question.text: What shape is the juice box?

g_3d_shapes_page3_mathcontext.text: I see a juice box. The juice box is a rectangular prism.

g_3d_shapes_page3_mathhint.text: Read about the juice box. What is its shape?

g_3d_shapes_page3_success.text: Great! The juice box is a rectangular prism.

g_3d_shapes_page4_sentence.text: I see a soda can. The soda can is a cylinder. It has 2 flat faces on the top and bottom. It has 1 curved edge. It can roll.

g_3d_shapes_page4_mathtip.text: A cylinder can roll. It has circles on the ends.

g_3d_shapes_page4_mathconcept.text: A cylinder has 2 flat circular faces and 1 curved surface

g_3d_shapes_page5_question.text: What shape is the soda can?

g_3d_shapes_page5_mathcontext.text: I see a soda can. The soda can is a cylinder.

g_3d_shapes_page5_mathhint.text: Read about the soda can. Find its shape.

g_3d_shapes_page5_success.text: Yes! The soda can is a cylinder.

g_3d_shapes_page6_menustory.text: The drink station has many choices. Each drink has a different shape. What will you choose?

g_3d_shapes_page7_sentence.text: I see an ice cream cone. The ice cream cone is a cone. It has 1 flat face on the bottom. It has 1 point at the top. It cannot roll.

g_3d_shapes_page7_mathtip.text: A cone has a point. It has a circle at the bottom.

g_3d_shapes_page7_mathconcept.text: A cone has 1 flat circular face and 1 point

g_3d_shapes_page8_question.text: What shape is the ice cream cone?

g_3d_shapes_page8_mathcontext.text: I see an ice cream cone. The ice cream cone is a cone.

g_3d_shapes_page8_mathhint.text: Read about the ice cream. What shape is it?

g_3d_shapes_page8_success.text: Nice! The ice cream cone is a cone.

g_3d_shapes_page9_sentence.text: I see ice cubes in my drink. Each ice cube is a cube. A cube has 6 square faces. All the faces are the same size.

g_3d_shapes_page9_mathtip.text: A cube is like a box. All sides are squares. All sides are equal.

g_3d_shapes_page9_mathconcept.text: A cube has 6 equal square faces

g_3d_shapes_page10_question.text: How many faces does a cube have?

g_3d_shapes_page10_mathcontext.text: I see ice cubes in my drink. A cube has 6 square faces.

g_3d_shapes_page10_mathhint.text: Count the faces of a cube. How many are there?

g_3d_shapes_page11_mathcontext.text: A cylinder can roll. A cone has a point and cannot roll. A cube has flat faces.

g_3d_shapes_page11_mathhint.text: Think about which shapes are round. Round shapes can roll.

g_3d_shapes_page12_question.text: Which shape has a point at the top?

g_3d_shapes_page12_mathcontext.text: A cone has 1 point at the top. A cylinder has flat ends. A cube has square faces.

g_3d_shapes_page12_mathhint.text: Think about the shapes. Which one comes to a point?

g_3d_shapes_page12_success.text: Nice! A cone has a point at the top.

g_compose_shapes_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Tile Workshop.

g_compose_shapes_page0_sentence.text: I arrive at the Tile Workshop. I see many tiles. The tiles are different shapes. I can put shapes together to make new shapes.

g_compose_shapes_page0_mathtip.text: When you put shapes together, you can make a new shape.

g_compose_shapes_page0_mathconcept.text: We can combine shapes to create new, bigger shapes

g_compose_shapes_page1_question.text: What can I do with shapes?

g_compose_shapes_page1_mathcontext.text: I see many tiles. The tiles are different shapes. I can put shapes together to make new shapes.

g_compose_shapes_page1_mathhint.text: Read the last sentence. What can I do?

g_compose_shapes_page1_success.text: Yes! You can put shapes together.

g_compose_shapes_page2_sentence.text: I take two triangles. I put them together. The two triangles make a square. I made a new shape from two shapes.

g_compose_shapes_page2_mathtip.text: When you put two right triangles together, they can make a square.

g_compose_shapes_page2_mathconcept.text: Two triangles can combine to make a square

g_compose_shapes_page3_question.text: What shape do two triangles make?

g_compose_shapes_page3_mathcontext.text: I take two triangles. I put them together. The two triangles make a square.

g_compose_shapes_page3_mathhint.text: Read about the two triangles. What do they make?

g_compose_shapes_page3_success.text: Great! Two triangles make a square.

g_compose_shapes_page4_sentence.text: I take two squares. I put them side by side. The two squares make a rectangle. The rectangle is longer than one square.

g_compose_shapes_page4_mathtip.text: When you put squares next to each other, you make a rectangle.

g_compose_shapes_page4_mathconcept.text: Two squares side by side make a rectangle

g_compose_shapes_page5_question.text: What do two squares make when you put them side by side?

g_compose_shapes_page5_mathcontext.text: I take two squares. I put them side by side. The two squares make a rectangle.

g_compose_shapes_page5_mathhint.text: Read the sentence. What shape do two squares make?

g_compose_shapes_page5_success.text: Yes! Two squares make a rectangle.

g_compose_shapes_page6_menustory.text: The workshop has many tile projects. Each one uses different shapes. What will you build?

g_compose_shapes_page7_sentence.text: I make a big triangle. I use three small triangles. I put them together carefully. Now I have one big triangle made from three small triangles.

g_compose_shapes_page7_mathtip.text: You can use small shapes to build bigger shapes.

g_compose_shapes_page7_mathconcept.text: Smaller shapes can combine to make larger shapes of the same type

g_compose_shapes_page8_question.text: How many small triangles did I use?

g_compose_shapes_page8_mathcontext.text: I make a big triangle. I use three small triangles. Now I have one big triangle made from three small triangles.

g_compose_shapes_page8_mathhint.text: Count how many small triangles I used.

g_compose_shapes_page9_question.text: I want to make a rectangle. Which shapes can I use?

g_compose_shapes_page9_mathcontext.text: Two squares make a rectangle. Two triangles can make a square. Shapes can combine to make new shapes.

g_compose_shapes_page9_mathhint.text: Think about what shapes combine to make a rectangle.

g_compose_shapes_page9_success.text: Great! Two squares make a rectangle.

g_compose_shapes_page10_question.text: What new shape can two triangles make?

g_compose_shapes_page10_mathcontext.text: I take two triangles. I put them together. The two triangles make a square.

g_compose_shapes_page10_mathhint.text: Remember what happened when we put two triangles together.

g_compose_shapes_page10_success.text: Yes! Two triangles can make a square.

g_compose_shapes_page11_question.text: I have 4 small squares. I put them in a 2 by 2 pattern. What shape do I make?

g_compose_shapes_page11_mathcontext.text: Small squares can combine to make bigger shapes. When you put 4 squares in a square pattern, you make a bigger square.

g_compose_shapes_page11_mathhint.text: Think about 4 squares in a square pattern. What big shape do they make?

g_compose_shapes_page11_success.text: Nice! 4 small squares make a big square.

g_halves_quarters_announcement.text: All aboard! Next stop: Pizza Party.

g_halves_quarters_page0_sentence.text: I arrive at the Pizza Party. I see pizzas and sandwiches. I need to share the food fairly. I will cut the food into equal parts.

g_halves_quarters_page0_mathtip.text: Equal parts means all the pieces are the same size.

g_halves_quarters_page0_mathconcept.text: Fair sharing means cutting into equal parts

g_halves_quarters_page1_mathcontext.text: I need to share the food fairly. I will cut the food into equal parts.

g_halves_quarters_page1_mathhint.text: Read about equal parts. What does it mean?

g_halves_quarters_page1_success.text: Yes! Equal parts are the same size.

g_halves_quarters_page2_sentence.text: I cut a pizza into 2 equal parts. Each part is called a half. There are 2 halves. The 2 halves make 1 whole pizza.

g_halves_quarters_page2_mathtip.text: When you cut something into 2 equal parts, each part is a half.

g_halves_quarters_page2_mathconcept.text: A half is 1 of 2 equal parts

g_halves_quarters_page3_question.text: How many halves are in 1 whole pizza?

g_halves_quarters_page3_mathcontext.text: I cut a pizza into 2 equal parts. There are 2 halves. The 2 halves make 1 whole pizza.

g_halves_quarters_page3_mathhint.text: Count the halves. How many equal parts?

g_halves_quarters_page3_success.text: Great! There are 2 halves in 1 whole.

g_halves_quarters_page4_sentence.text: I cut a sandwich into 4 equal parts. Each part is called a fourth. Each part is also called a quarter. There are 4 fourths. The 4 fourths make 1 whole sandwich.

g_halves_quarters_page4_mathtip.text: When you cut into 4 equal parts, each part is a fourth or a quarter.

g_halves_quarters_page4_mathconcept.text: A fourth or quarter is 1 of 4 equal parts

g_halves_quarters_page5_question.text: How many fourths are in 1 whole sandwich?

g_halves_quarters_page5_mathcontext.text: I cut a sandwich into 4 equal parts. There are 4 fourths. The 4 fourths make 1 whole sandwich.

g_halves_quarters_page5_mathhint.text: Count the fourths. How many equal parts?

g_halves_quarters_page5_success.text: Yes! There are 4 fourths in 1 whole.

g_halves_quarters_page6_menustory.text: The party has different foods to share. Each one can be cut into equal parts. What will you share?

g_halves_quarters_page7_question.text: What is another name for a fourth?

g_halves_quarters_page7_mathcontext.text: Each part is called a fourth. Each part is also called a quarter.

g_halves_quarters_page7_mathhint.text: Read about fourths. What is another name?

g_halves_quarters_page7_success.text: Nice! A fourth is also called a quarter.

g_halves_quarters_page8_sentence.text: I need to share a cookie with my friend. I cut it into 2 equal parts. We each get 1 half. This is a fair share.

g_halves_quarters_page8_mathtip.text: When we share fairly, everyone gets the same amount.

g_halves_quarters_page8_mathconcept.text: Sharing fairly means each person gets an equal part

g_halves_quarters_page9_question.text: I want to share a pizza with 3 friends. How many equal parts do I need?

g_halves_quarters_page9_mathcontext.text: I need to share fairly. I cut into equal parts. Each person gets 1 equal part.

g_halves_quarters_page9_mathhint.text: Count how many people. You and 3 friends is 4 people total.

g_halves_quarters_page10_mathcontext.text: A half is 1 of 2 equal parts. When I cut into 2 equal parts, I make halves.

g_halves_quarters_page10_mathhint.text: Think about halves. How many parts are there?

g_halves_quarters_page11_mathcontext.text: A fourth is 1 of 4 equal parts. When I cut into 4 equal parts, I make fourths.

g_halves_quarters_page11_mathhint.text: Think about fourths. How many parts are there?

g_halves_quarters_page12_mathcontext.text: I see a pizza cut into 2 parts. One part is big. One part is small. These parts are not equal.

g_halves_quarters_page12_mathhint.text: Look at the two parts. Are they the same size?

g_halves_quarters_page12_success.text: Right! The parts are not equal.
